    int y;

    MyClass(int newX, int newY) : y(newY), x(newX) { // Warning: 'MyClass::y' will be initialized after 'MyClass::x'
        // Constructor body
    }
};
```

In the above example, the member `y` is initialized before `x` in the constructor initialization list, but `x` is declared before `y` in the class. This can be misleading to someone reading the code since it suggests that `y` will be initialized before `x`, which is not the case.

To fix this warning, simply reorder the initialization list to match the declaration order:

```cpp
